ggplot(counted_sex, aes(x = sex, y = n, fill = sex)) +
  labs(x = "Sex", y = "Count", fill = "Sex") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("pink", "lightblue")) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") 

#4 Create a filled density plot showing the relationship between year and sex.
#Set transparency anywehere between 30-50%. Give your plot a title, subtitle, and label the axes. 

ggplot(babynames, aes(x = year, fill = sex)) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Year by Sex",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Density",
       fill = "Sex") +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3)

#7 Create a scatter plot showing the relationship between the number of carats and price of diamonds controlling for the cut.
#Give your plot a title. To fix the issue of overplotting, change either transparency or shape of data points (refer to help section within RStudio for guidance). 
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price, color = cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, aes(shape = cut)) +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Carats and Price of Diamonds by Cut",
    x = "Carats",
    y = "Price"
  )
## Warning: Using shapes for an ordinal variable is not advised
